Ok, so sorry for the continued push back on this, but I'm still a having a hard time accepting the additional concept of triggers into the library when it can perhaps be achieved in different ways.

As I understand it, essentially this is something (the trigger) that will run *before* any handlers so that flags can be twiddled before handlers conditions' are evaluated.

Conceptually, this is very similar to using a preflight type decorator.  To avoid confusing those two concepts:

```python
@run_before_any_handlers
def twiddle_config():
    if flag('config.changed'):
        set_flag('mylayer.config.changed')
    else:
        clear_flag('mylayer.config.changed')  # just to make sure!
```

The key here, for me, is to try to keep things simple, but also enable resolving a bit of the _can't determine the order that things are run in_ issue.  The syntax above is similar to preconditions and allows you to do more things than a trigger would (although, conceptually, you could make the trigger call a function).  In fact, the trigger could be re-written as:

```python
@trigger(event='config.changed')
def the_config_has_changed():
    set_flag('mylayer.config.changed')
```

Custom events, and triggers, seems to add _more_ to the charms.reactive library, but one of the goals is to do less.

Can you move some logic from `_operands` to visitors? The visitors are doing to mapping that it's done here https://github.com/inveniosoftware/invenio/pull/2956/files#diff-d96416206488cc09b0c53ea3907f8d84R169

Example:
```python
@staticmethod
def operands(node, operand, value):
    ...

@visitor(LowerOp)
def visit(self, node, value):
    return self._operators(node, 'lt', value()["multi_match"]["query"])
```
